<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/uskolian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skolian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>n00b!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/10/02 9:13:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11945.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fantastic book series</span><hr size=1> Here is the top of my very very long list of favorites ordered from best to slightly less good order<br>
<br>
By far the best series comming out atm IMHO is George Martin's A Song of Ice and Fire books.<br>
<br>
Anything by Guy Gavriel Kay, especially Tigana, and Lions of Al-Rasan.<br>
<br>
Dune is my all time favorite Science Fiction novel.  A must read!<br>
<br>
Yeah, I also love the Miles Vorkosigan series.  My favorite science fiction series.  Reading Bujold's newest Diplomatic Immunity atm.<br>
<br>
Dan Simmons Hyperion novels are also a must read.  These books can get creepy at times.<br>
<br>
Anything by Tim Powers.  Declare, Last Call, and Anubis Gates are all must reads.<br>
<br>
Anything by Steven Brust.  The Vlad Taltos books are must read.  My old old account was loiosh@sfsu.edu from this series.<br>
<br>
Although I'm not a big Feist fan, the Empire trilogy he wrote with J Wurts was good.<br>
<br>
Vernor Vinge's Fire Upon the Deep and A Deepness in the Sky are my favorite hard science fiction novels.  Somewhat like David Brin, but much better IMO.<br>
<br>
Catherine Asaro's Skolian Empire novels.  Good fun, even if they do borderline as romance novels.<br>
<br>
Of course the Lord of the Rings.  nuff said.<br>
<br>
The Amber Chronicles which inspired the best pen and paper role playing game by the same name.<br>
<br>
Kage Baker's Company novels.  Great steam punk adventures.<br>
<br>
The Black Company series by Glen Cook.  These books are so goonie.  My old account was murgen@att.net which is also a character from this series.<br>
<br>
Ender's Game and Speaker are also decent books, but find most of the other Card books very similar in plots and characters.<br>
<br>
Ken Macleod's books.  Great hard science fiction from a newer author.<br>
<br>
Connie Willis.  She has so many awards.  I love her short stories.<br>
<br>
Katherine Kerr, not to be mistaken with Catherine Kurtz (also good).  Her stories of reincarnation and magic are awesome.<br>
<br>
I'm odd in that I like Gibson's new cyberpunk trilogy (Virtual Light, Idoru, All Tomorrows Parties) better than his first set.<br>
<br>
I suppose I'll stop there, since most of the books that follow start to get even more mainstream and people are familiar with them (Waystation, Heilein's stuff, Riftwar books, etc.)<br>
<br>
-Baron Kovar, Hugo voter <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/uthurinielthewanderingmage.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thuriniel the Wandering Mage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I <3 Mistmoore</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/10/02 9:58:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11945.topic&index=64>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fantastic book series</span><hr size=1> Oh yeah, James Clavell's Asian novels.  Well, all of them but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gai-Jin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. <p>Thuriniel Zomm 54 mage<br>
